      "explanation": "Why \"Semicircular canals\" is correct:\n- The semicircular canals are part of the vestibular system in the inner ear that detect rotational movement and help maintain balance.\n- They contain fluid and hair cells that bend when the head moves, sending signals to the brain about angular acceleration and deceleration.\n- There are three canals oriented in different planes (horizontal, anterior, posterior) to detect movement in all directions.\n- Information from the semicircular canals is integrated with visual and proprioceptive input in the cerebellum for balance control.\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"Cochlea\" is wrong because it is the spiral-shaped structure responsible for hearing, converting sound vibrations into electrical signals.\n- \"Ossicles\" is wrong because they are the three tiny bones (malleus, incus, stapes) in the middle ear that transmit sound vibrations.\n- \"Eardrum\" is wrong because it is the tympanic membrane that vibrates in response to sound waves but does not detect balance."
