      "questionText": "Which hormone is responsible for male secondary sexual characters?",
      "correctAnswer": "Testosterone",
      "explanation": "Why \"Testosterone\" is correct:\n- Testosterone is the primary male sex hormone produced by the testes that stimulates the development of male secondary sexual characteristics during puberty.\n- It promotes muscle development, deepening of the voice, growth of facial and body hair, and increased bone density.\n- Testosterone also plays a crucial role in sperm production and maintains male reproductive function throughout adulthood.\n- The hormone influences behavior, energy levels, and libido, contributing to typical male physical and behavioral traits.\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"Estrogen\" is wrong because it is the primary female sex hormone that promotes female secondary characteristics like breast development and wider hips.\n- \"Progesterone\" is wrong because it is involved in the menstrual cycle and pregnancy maintenance, not male secondary sexual development.\n- \"Insulin\" is wrong because it is a metabolic hormone that regulates blood sugar levels, not sexual development or characteristics."
