      "points": 1,
      "questionText": "Fungi are different from plants because they lack:",
      "correctAnswer": "Chlorophyll",
      "explanation": "Why \"Chlorophyll\" is correct:\n- Fungi lack chlorophyll, the green pigment that allows plants to carry out photosynthesis and produce their own food using sunlight.\n- Instead, fungi are heterotrophs that obtain nutrients by absorbing organic matter from their environment or hosts.\n- This fundamental difference places fungi in their own kingdom, separate from plants, and explains why they don't grow in sunlight like plants do.\n- Fungi include mushrooms, yeasts, and molds, all of which cannot make their own food through photosynthesis.\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"Nucleus\" is wrong because fungi have eukaryotic cells with nuclei containing their genetic material.\n- \"Cell wall\" is wrong because fungi have cell walls made of chitin, similar to insects, though different from plant cellulose.\n- \"Cytoplasm\" is wrong because fungi have cytoplasm that contains organelles and carries out cellular functions."
