      "explanation": "\"six days\" is correct because the creation account in Genesis describes God creating the world in six days and resting on the seventh day. The seventh day was not a day of creation, but a day of divine rest, blessing, and completion. \"Seven days\" sounds tempting because many students remember the total weekly structure, but the actual days of creative work are six. \"Five days\" and \"eight days\" do not match the Biblical order at all. The lesson is that Genesis presents creation as orderly, purposeful, and complete under God's command."
