      "explanation": "Why \"Foucault's Pendulum\" is correct:\n- Semiotics is the philosophical study of signs and symbols. As a professional semiotician, Umberto Eco infused all his novels with these concepts, but \"Foucault's Pendulum\" is the most explicit exploration of how humans interpret and misinterpret signs.\n- The novel demonstrates how a series of random or disconnected historical \"signs\" can be woven into a compelling (but false) narrative, highlighting the power and the danger of the interpretative process.\n- While \"The Name of the Rose\" also deals with signs, \"Foucault's Pendulum\" is more specifically focused on the theoretical mechanics of semiotics in the modern world.\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"The Name of the Rose,\" \"The Island of the Day Before,\" and \"Baudolino\" are other novels by Eco that involve semiotics to varying degrees but are not the primary answer for this question."
