      "questionText": "The basic economic problem is about",
      "correctAnswer": "scarcity and choice",
      "explanation": "Why \"scarcity and choice\" is correct:\n- The fundamental economic problem is scarcity, which means that human wants are unlimited while the resources available to satisfy those wants are limited. Because we cannot have everything we want, we must make choices about how to allocate our limited resources effectively.\n- Choice is the direct result of scarcity; every time we choose one thing, we give up something else (this is known as opportunity cost).\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"production and consumption\" are essential economic activities, but they are ways we deal with the problem, not the problem itself.\n- \"money and banking\" refers to the financial system that facilitates exchange, but scarcity exists even in societies without money.\n- \"trade and commerce\" involves the exchange of goods and services, which helps manage scarcity, but the core problem remains the limited nature of resources vs. unlimited wants."
