      "questionText": "The law of demand states that",
      "correctAnswer": "price and quantity demanded are inversely related",
      "explanation": "Why \"price and quantity demanded are inversely related\" is correct:\n- The Law of Demand is a fundamental principle which states that, all other factors being equal (ceteris paribus), as the price of a good increases, the quantity demanded decreases. Conversely, as the price of a good decreases, the quantity demanded increases.\n- This \"inverse relationship\" means price and quantity move in opposite directions. It is visually represented by a downward-sloping demand curve.\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"price and quantity demanded are directly related\" describes an exceptional situation (like Giffen goods or Veblen goods) but contradicts the general Law of Demand.\n- \"price and quantity supplied are inversely related\" is incorrect because supply typically has a direct relationship with price.\n- \"price and quantity supplied are directly related\" actually describes the Law of Supply, not the Law of Demand."
