      "questionText": "The law of supply states that",
      "correctAnswer": "price and quantity supplied are directly related",
      "explanation": "Why \"price and quantity supplied are directly related\" is correct:\n- The Law of Supply states that, ceteris paribus (all else being equal), an increase in the price of a good results in an increase in the quantity supplied. This happens because higher prices offer higher profit potential, encouraging producers to bring more of the product to the market.\n- This \"direct relationship\" means price and quantity move in the same direction, resulting in an upward-sloping supply curve.\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"price and quantity supplied are inversely related\" is incorrect as it contradicts the basic motivation of producers to sell more at higher prices.\n- \"price and quantity demanded are directly related\" is incorrect and generally violates the Law of Demand.\n- \"price and quantity demanded are inversely related\" describes the Law of Demand, not the Law of Supply."
