      "questionText": "Elasticity measures",
      "correctAnswer": "responsiveness of quantity to price changes",
      "explanation": "Why \"responsiveness of quantity to price changes\" is correct:\n- In economics, elasticity is a measure of how much one variable responds to changes in another variable. Most commonly, \"price elasticity\" measures how sensitive the quantity demanded (or supplied) is to a change in the price of that good.\n- If a small change in price leads to a large change in quantity, the good is said to be \"elastic.\" If quantity hardly changes when price moves, it is \"inelastic.\"\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"total revenue\" is the total amount of money a firm receives (Price x Quantity); while elasticity affects total revenue, it is not a measure of it.\n- \"profit maximization\" is a goal where Marginal Revenue equals Marginal Cost (MR=MC), not a measurement of responsiveness.\n- \"cost minimization\" is a production strategy to produce a given level of output at the lowest possible cost, unrelated to the concept of elasticity."
