      "questionText": "Price elasticity of demand is calculated as",
      "correctAnswer": "% change in quantity demanded / % change in price",
      "explanation": "Why \"% change in quantity demanded / % change in price\" is correct:\n- The formula for Price Elasticity of Demand (PED) is designed to show the percentage change in the quantity demanded relative to the percentage change in price. We use percentages so that the measure is independent of the units used (like kilograms vs. pounds).\n- Formula: PED = (% Change in Quantity Demanded) / (% Change in Price).\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"% change in price / % change in quantity demanded\" is the reciprocal of the correct formula and would give an incorrect value.\n- \"change in quantity / change in price\" measures the slope of the demand curve, but elasticity requires percentage changes to be accurate across different price levels.\n- \"change in price / change in quantity\" is also a slope measurement (and the reciprocal of the one above), not the standard formula for elasticity."
