      "explanation": "Why \"horizontal\" is correct:\n- Perfectly elastic demand (elasticity = infinity) occurs when consumers are prepared to buy any amount of a good at a specific price, but will buy zero if the price rises even slightly. This results in a horizontal line on a graph.\n- This is often seen in perfectly competitive markets where many sellers provide an identical product, and no single seller can raise their price above the market rate.\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"vertical\" represents perfectly inelastic demand, where quantity doesn't change regardless of price.\n- \"upward sloping\" generally describes a supply curve, not a demand curve.\n- \"downward sloping\" describes normal, relatively elastic or inelastic demand, but not \"perfectly\" elastic demand."
