      "explanation": "Why \"positive income elasticity\" is correct:\n- A \"normal good\" is defined as a good for which demand increases as consumer income rises. Because both variables (income and quantity demanded) move in the same direction, the income elasticity of demand is a positive number.\n- Examples include fresh fruit, new clothes, or dining at restaurants—things people buy more of when they have more money.\n\nWhy the other options are not correct:\n- \"negative income elasticity\" defines an \"inferior good,\" which people buy less of as they get richer (like instant noodles or used clothes).\n- \"zero income elasticity\" would mean demand doesn't change at all with income, which is rare.\n- \"infinite income elasticity\" is a theoretical extreme not used to define normal goods."
